      <title>Sahara desert climate alters every 20,000 years</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA new study by MIT researchers suggests that the Sahara desert may have once flourished with nature.Their analysis of marine sediment from the West African coast suggests that the Sahara's climate alters between dry and wet every 20,000 years. The researchers believe this "climatic pendulum" is caused by changes to Earth's axis as it rotates around the sun.This in turn affects the amount of sunlight the Earth receives during different seasons.As the planet tilts to receive maximum sunlight, it intensifies periods of monsoon rain which results in a "greener" Sahara. When the Earth tilts toward an angle that doesn't allow it to receive as much sunlight, the Sahara gets a more arid climate.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. A green Sahara desert with plants and animals2. Inset of ocean sediments and we see the Sahara desert turning green3. Earth rotating in space4. The Earth tilts toward the sun, which results in rain and the desert turns green5. The Earth tilts away from the sun, which turns the desert dry and aridVOICEOVER (in English): "A new study by MIT researchers suggests that the Sahara desert may have once flourished with nature.""Their analysis of marine sediment from the West African coast suggests that the Sahara's climate alters between dry and wet every 20,000 years.""The researchers believe this 'climatic pendulum'  is caused by changes to Earth's axis as it rotates around the sun.""As the planet tilts to receive maximum sunlight, it intensifies periods of monsoon rain which results in a 'greener' Sahara.""When the Earth tilts toward an angle that doesn't allow it to receive as much sunlight, the Sahara gets a more arid climate."SOURCES: Phys.org, MIT, Science Advances, https://phys.org/news/2019-01-sahara-swung-lush-conditions-years.htmlhttp://news.mit.edu/2019/study-regulating-north-african-climate-0102http://advances.sciencemag.org/content/5/1/eaav1887***]]></description>
