      <title>Less than six hours sleep per night may increase heart disease risk, study says</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANPeople who sleep less than six hours a night might have an increased risk of cardiovascular disease compared to those who sleep seven to eight hours, according to a new study published in the Journal of the American College of Cardiology.  According to UPI, the study published on Jan. 14 found that chronic lack of sleep or poor sleep quality were associated with increased chances of atherosclerosis, a condition where fatty plaque accumulates in the arteries which can lead to heart attack or stroke. For the study, lead researcher Jose Ordovas from the National Center for Cardiovascular Research in Madrid and his team tracked around 4,000 Spanish adults using coronary ultrasound and CT scans to monitor artery health. Participants did not have a prior history of heart disease at the start of the study and had an average age of 46. Researchers was unable to prove cause and effect, but they found people who slept less than six hours a night were 27 percent more likely to have body-wide atherosclerosis than those who slept seven to eight hours a night. The study also found that women who slept more than eight hours a night had an increased chance of atherosclerosis. Adults with poor-quality sleep were also 34 percent more likely to have atherosclerosis, compared to individuals with good-quality sleep. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. People who sleep less than 6 hours a night have increased heart disease risk2. Atherosclerosis3. Participants monitored with CT scans and coronary ultrasound; people who slept less than 6 hours have higher rates of atherosclerosis4. People with poor quality sleep and women who slept more than 8 hours had higher rates of atherosclerosisVOICEOVER (in English): "According to a new study published in the Journal of the American College of Cardiology on Jan 14, people who sleep less than six hours a night might have an increased risk of cardiovascular disease compared to those who sleep seven to eight hours."  "According to UPI, the study found that chronic lack of sleep or poor sleep quality were associated with increased chances of atherosclerosis, a condition where fatty plaque accumulates in the arteries which can lead to heart attack or stroke." "Researchers tracked around 4,000 Spanish adults using coronary ultrasound and CT scans to monitor artery health." "They were unable to prove cause and effect, but found people who slept less than six hours a night were 27 percent more likely to have body-wide atherosclerosis than those who slept seven to eight hours a night." "Adults with poor-quality sleep were also 34 percent more likely to have atherosclerosis, compared to individuals with good-quality sleep." "The study also found that women who slept more than eight hours a night had an increased chance of atherosclerosis." SOURCES: UPIhttps://www.upi.com/Health_News/2019/01/14/Study-Less-than-six-hours-sleep-per-night-increases-risk-for-heart-disease/8491547500288/***]]></description>
