      <title>Denmark to build nine artificial islands off the coast of Copenhagen</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe Danish government and greater Copenhagen mayors have revealed plans to build artificial islands using surplus soil from construction projects, according to a report by New Atlas.The Urban Power architecture and planning firm has designed the project, called "Holmene," which calls for the creation a total of nine artificial islands 10 km off the coast of Copenhagen by 2040.The islands will be built one by one, with the government hoping to start construction on the first island by 2022.The government plans to finance the project by selling plots on the islands to different businesses.Soil from construction projects as well as imported Swedish surplus soil will be used to create the islands, according to Holmene's website.One of the islands would house a waste water conversion plant as well as windmills to store energy, Deutsche Welle reports. Some of the other islands would be used for recreational purposes, according to the project's website.The project would ease the problem of land shortage in Denmark by creating 3 million square meters of new land for Denmark, Deutsche Welle reports.This would result in 17 kilometers of new coastline, 700,000 square meters of nature and space for upto 380 new businesses, Deutsche Welle reports.Danish chamber of commerce Brian Mikkelsen, saying this to TV2 televisionThe artificial islands are projected to bring in more than $8 billion in economic activity.The Guardian quotes Brian Mikkelsen, head of the Danish chamber of commerce, as telling TV2 television he thinks the project "could become a sort of European Silicon Valley."RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The artificial islands on a map2. The artificial islands being built one by one3. The soil that would be used to create the islands4.  An island with a waste water conversion plant, windmills and a recreational parkVOICEOVER (in English): "The Urban Power architecture and planning firm has designed the project, called 'Holmene,' which calls for the creation a total of nine artificial islands 10 kilometers off the coast of Copenhagen by 2040.""The islands will be built one by one, with the government hoping to start construction on the first island by 2022.""Soil from construction projects as well as imported Swedish surplus soil will be used to create the islands, according to Holmene's website.""One of the islands would house a waste water conversion plant as well as windmills to store energy, Deutsche Welle reports.""While some of the other islands would be used for recreational purposes, according to the project's website."SOURCES: Deutsche Welle, Holmene, Urban Power, https://www.dw.com/en/denmark-plans-silicon-valley-on-9-artificial-islands-off-copenhagen/a-46986197http://holmene.com/Nyt-erhvervsomraade/FAQhttp://www.urbanpower.dk/holmene.html***]]></description>
