      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANRelativity Space's 3D printed rocket could be launching from Cape Canaveral before the end of 2020.Relativity Space made different parts for their new rocket, Terran-1, using their 3D printer Stargate, according to the company's website.The Terran-1 would take around 60 days to print. When all the parts are put together, the rocket would be around 100-feet tall. It would also be able to carry a payload of nearly 2,750 pounds.Relativity Space has also received permission from the U.S. Air Force to launch Terran-1 at Cape Canaveral in Florida.The company is hoping to launch the 3D-printed rocket by the end of 2020.If the launch is successful, the company could get to lease the site for up to 20 years, according to Business Insider.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Terran-1 rocket and Stargate, a 3D printer2. The rocket from bottom to top and its payload3. Launch Complex 164. Terran-1 rocket being launchedVOICEOVER (in English): "Relativity Space made different parts for their new rocket, Terran-1, using their 3D printer Stargate, according to the company's website.""All in all, the Terran-1 would take around 60 days to print. "When all the parts are put together, the rocket would be around 100-feet tall." "It would also be able to carry a payload of nearly 2,750 pounds.""Relativity Space has also received permission from the U.S. Air Force to launch Terran-1 at Cape Canaveral in Florida.""The company is hoping to launch the 3D-printed rocket by the end of 2020."SOURCES: Futurism.com, Quartz, Business Insider, Florida Today, Relativity Spacehttps://futurism.com/air-force-grants-launch-site-3d-printed-rocket-relativity-spacehttps://qz.com/1526158/rocket-start-up-relativity-leased-a-